56:55.382 --> 56:57.766
So there's a transition in the century.

56:57.806 --> 57:02.555
Are these calls from your own collections?

57:02.575 --> 57:04.038
Don't you know the old trick?

57:04.058 --> 57:07.464
I was talking to Sada about this.

57:07.624 --> 57:09.608
I said, we did all these exhibitions.

57:09.942 --> 57:15.728
I know why he did the exhibition, not to show the books, but to justify buying them, to put them in the exhibition.

57:15.989 --> 57:20.594
You know, it's just fun.

57:20.754 --> 57:23.817
Life offers so many interesting opportunities.

57:25.139 --> 57:32.727
Here, just to show you another aspect, if I'm interested in music things, here are a couple of other things.

57:34.158 --> 57:38.644
This is another project that I started quite by accident.

57:41.027 --> 57:44.331
It helps if you're slightly demented.

57:44.511 --> 57:58.889
Back in the 1880s, my great-grandfather was in the newspaper business in Ohio, and he worked with a guy named Frank Pixley in the mid-1880s in Akron, Ohio, P-I-X-L-E-Y.

58:00.231 --> 58:01.072
That's chapter one.

58:01.152 --> 58:03.355
Chapter two is I'm at Illinois Wesley.

58:03.588 --> 58:08.192
We have a program in music theater, school of art, and school of drama.

58:08.212 --> 58:09.914
And I'm going to a flea market.

58:10.314 --> 58:15.999
The library hasn't had, so far, too much of a collection on music theater.

58:16.880 --> 58:24.307
So I think, well, gee, how many examples of music theater can I get in piles of sheet music for real cheap?

58:25.488 --> 58:33.375
I find, when I'm there, I forget whether it was the Prince of Pilsen or King Dodo.

58:34.334 --> 58:41.523
a show from Chicago with the music by Gustav Luters and the music by Frank Pixley.

58:42.144 --> 58:50.093
And I said, this sounds like the same guy who worked with my own great-grandfather in Ohio in the 1880s and must be a relative.

58:50.354 --> 58:51.135
It's no relative.

58:51.275 --> 58:52.697
It's the same guy.

58:53.458 --> 58:55.560
He had left Ohio, come to Chicago.

58:55.580 --> 58:57.102
He was editor of a newspaper.

58:57.554 --> 59:01.458
And on the side, he used to write the words for musicals.

59:01.478 --> 59:04.822
This led me to get interested in Chicago Musical Theater.

59:05.202 --> 59:13.371
No one else, seemingly, so far as I can tell, ever made a list of musicals before 1920, launched in Chicago.

59:13.451 --> 59:17.875
But there you have, this is for you, an attempt at it.

59:18.936 --> 59:23.241
You know, again, I just started doing this because

59:23.727 --> 59:27.812
I was finding the stuff, and nobody else had it, so I thought I put it in.

59:27.832 --> 59:29.555
Obviously, you found all the stuff around here, then.

59:29.955 --> 59:37.165
Well, around here, from dealers in New England, or dealers would send me a box through the mail.

59:37.185 --> 59:38.867
Yeah, yeah.

59:40.369 --> 59:42.813
And I think there are about 120 shows.

59:42.833 --> 59:47.439
One of my colleagues in music is actually thinking of doing a book on Chicago musical theater.

59:47.499 --> 59:49.501
Now, I talked and talked and talked about it.

59:49.521 --> 59:50.323
She got interested.

59:50.343 --> 59:53.667
Babies in Toyland starts in Chicago before it goes to New York.

59:54.187 --> 59:58.593
A lot of this stuff never goes much of anywhere, but that's why I called it.

59:58.613 --> 01:00:05.262
There was a show called The Winning Miss, and that I think is a very good subset for Chicago Musical Theater.

01:00:05.282 --> 01:00:08.346
It was great out here, but it kind of missed when it got to New York.

01:00:13.092 --> 01:00:15.436
Are any of these particularly scarce?

01:00:15.456 --> 01:00:17.719
Do you think any of them exist?

01:00:17.739 --> 01:00:18.760
I'll tell you.

01:00:19.094 --> 01:00:22.798
That's what's so interesting, and why does Yahoo throw it out?

01:00:22.858 --> 01:00:36.150
Because I, as a sophomore working for a junior assistant librarian who just finished library school, surely knows that I am about to throw out the only excellent example of something.

01:00:36.591 --> 01:00:37.952
It's even more insidious than that.

01:00:37.972 --> 01:00:39.994
This kid's an employee.

01:00:40.014 --> 01:00:41.115
These people are employed.

01:00:41.495 --> 01:00:44.078
These are not students doing this.

01:00:44.238 --> 01:00:46.300
This is policy.

